Marrakech,05QDGvi0_sM,Ugy2i1kHF78TdRur4d14AaABAg.AIsxJuMdhOhAIt0zSG6V5n,Ugy2i1kHF78TdRur4d14AaABAg,@FindingGinaMarie,"Hi Lily, You could take a Fes to Chefchaouen day trip for $85 per person and just not take the return. There also are several CTM buses operating on this route daily. If you're trying to then get from Chefchaouen to Casablanca, there are buses and trains that also are an option. Thanks for watching! —Judy
🎥 Morocco Travel Series: https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLNT98lWfwdF0_pL4S2LnqlBz2KBX9XMCc",2025-06-02T21:58:16Z,2025-06-02T21:58:16Z,1,True,,2026-05-10T02:01:50.444048
Marrakech,05QDGvi0_sM,Ugzv44djICdpC_RdHsd4AaABAg.AIOCPtJdp8ZAIOH_WYRNMv,Ugzv44djICdpC_RdHsd4AaABAg,@FindingGinaMarie,"Hi Donna, Knees and shoulders is more of a Western modesty ideal when you're heading into a church. Some Muslim women are covered head to toe. But at the same time, Marrakech and Fes and Chefchaouen are pretty tolerant of Westerners. We noticed a wide range of dress among locals and visitors alike. You don't need to wear headscarves anywhere, especially since you're not allowed in a mosque if you're not a Muslim (in Morocco). I felt my clothes were reasonably modest while also being comfortable for the heat. As long as you're not baring your midriff, showing off too much cleavage, or showing off your thighs, I think you're good. Bear in mind that some Moroccans wear more clothes because they're also trying not to tan too much/protect their skin versus exclusively for modesty purposes. We hope you have a terrific time in Morocco! —Judy
