Tourism,ET9-7Ooh3O8,UgydsDz_M7oyL36NJld4AaABAg,,@byronjohnson821,"For the best BEEF (NOT pork) ribs in Texas hands down, try County Line BBQ in Austin where the chain originated.  Moist, generous servings and you don't have to sit in an un-air-conditioned shed in 100º+F Texas summer heat.  Riscky's BBQ passed to a new family of owners in 2005 and sadly isn't what it was--we'll be nice an call it a tourist attraction for Californians.  PS---the location in Ft Worth was not a ranch, it was a stockyards rail head in the 1870s-80s where cattle were sold and shipped in for meat processing.  My friend, NEVER, NEVER order the ""all you can eat"" special ANYWHERE or what you get will be like a Golden Corral buffet come on.  What you call ""moist"" is beef fat which gives it taste and ""moistness"".  Unfortunately, the ""All You Can Eat"" joint ribs are (over) cooked practically to jerky en masse for the tourists until all the beef fat is gone.  Sorry you wasted a plane ticket and trip.   If you want the BEST CHILI DOG try the Dog House drive-in on Central Avenue (Route 66) near Old Town in Albuquerque, NM opened in 1948. Their foot longs with cheese and onions are simple, spicy, greasy, cheesy and old school. When I worked in ABQ in the 70's-90's I had 1-1/2 chili dogs for dinner once a week!  Good channel.",2026-05-10T01:17:45Z,2026-05-10T01:41:15Z,0,False,0.0,2026-05-10T02:02:18.348750
